# Standards — The Vanishing Paintings

## Prose That Looks Fine But Isn't

```
CLUE PLANTED AND SOLVED IN THE SAME SCENE:
"Maya noticed the scratch on the display case. It was exactly the kind
of mark a lockpick would leave — three parallel lines, evenly spaced,
right next to the latch mechanism. Someone had picked this lock."

The reader didn't get to figure anything out. The detective solved
it for them in the same paragraph she found it. Plant the scratch.
Let Maya notice it. Let her NOT understand it. The reader figures
it out three chapters later when they learn what lockpick marks look like.
```

```
DEUS EX MACHINA:
"Maya was stuck. She'd been staring at the clue wall for an hour.
Then her mom walked in, glanced at the photos, and said 'Oh, that's
obviously the janitor's master key pattern.' Mystery solved."

A 10-year-old beta reader said: "That's not fair. I wanted to figure
it out." Adults don't solve kids' mysteries. Ever.
```

```
THE INFO DUMP:
"As you know, Oliver," Maya said, "the museum uses a Kensington lock
system installed in 1987, which requires a seven-pin tumbler mechanism
that can only be operated with a registered key card..."

Two characters explaining things they both already know, for the
reader's benefit. Show the lock. Show it not opening. Don't lecture.
```

```
TELLING INSTEAD OF SHOWING:
"Maya felt scared. She was very nervous about going into the dark room.
She was anxious and her heart was beating fast."

vs.

"Maya's hand tightened on the sketchbook. She made herself breathe —
in for four, hold, out for four — the way the counselor taught her."

The second one never says "scared." The reader feels it anyway.
```

```
CHAPTER THAT ENDS AT A STOPPING POINT:
"Maya closed her notebook, said goodnight to Oliver, and went to bed.
It had been a long day."

The beta reader put the book down and didn't pick it up for two days.
End mid-tension. Mid-discovery. Mid-danger. Never where it's
comfortable to stop reading.
```

```
FLAT DIALOGUE — everyone sounds the same:
"I think we should check the loading dock," Maya said.
"I think that's a good idea," Oliver said.
"I think we should be careful," Dr. Winters said.

Maya is precise: "The loading dock log doesn't match Tuesday's schedule."
Oliver is impulsive: "Let's just go look."
Winters is nervous: "I'm not sure that's — I mean, should we really —"
```

## When to Go Deeper

When plotting or structuring chapters, read `.claude/references/mystery-craft.md` — especially revelation pacing and plant-and-payoff patterns.
When writing dialogue or prose, read `.claude/references/mystery-craft.md` — especially clue types and red herring design.
When a reader reports pacing problems or boredom, read `.claude/references/mystery-craft.md` — check revelation pacing for the chapter range, verify every chapter earns its length, and audit clue density in the flagged section.
When changing setting, characters, or plot structure, read `.claude/references/mystery-craft.md` — verify the fair-play rules still hold and no clue chains are broken by the change.
When writing a new chapter, read `.claude/references/mystery-craft.md` — check where this chapter sits in revelation pacing and what clue types are due.
